Testing your code

The first step in QA/QC is making sure your code is reliable. The concept of testing code for errors or mistaken assumptions is common in programming. For data science and statistical computing, testing code is very open ended and often underutilized. Its a good habit to get into. In R there is no built in function for evaluating a statement and returning an error message. Here you will learn to create your own function. In general creating functions is helpful when you want to repeatedly use a few lines of codes or calculations. Lets create a function called assert (python users, you will be used to this function) that checks whether a logical statement is true and returns an error message if it is false.

#create a function. The names of the arguments for your function will be in parentheses. Everything in curly brackets will be run each time the function is run.
assert <- function(statement,err.message){
  #if evaluates if a statement is true or false for a single item
  if(statement == FALSE){
    print(err.message)
  }
  
}

#check how the statement works
#evaluate a false statement
assert(1 == 2, "error: unequal values")
## [1] "error: unequal values"
#evaluate a true statement
assert(2 == 2, "error: unequal values")
#set up assert to check if two vectors are the same length
a <- c(1,2,3,4)
b <- c(8,4,5)
assert(length(a) == length(b), "error: unequal length")
## [1] "error: unequal length"

This kind of test is helpful for checking that your code or data is functioning as you expect. For example, you may want to check that different data objects have the properties you expect or your calculations are producing the right values. Once successful, these tests may not seem necessary to keep in your code. However, they are because it shows that you are checking the accuracy of your code. It also is good for keeping track of what you checked for versus what you may have missed.

That means if there are characters in rows 2, 3 and numbers in the rest of the rows, R will default to treating the data as either a character or a factor. This is problematic when you want to only work with the numbers. This means that we will have to read in the csv in a couple of steps.The other problem is that the datalogger stores NA as #N/A. Data QA/QC

Here our quality assurance will consist of making sure we dont have any abnormal measurements or use data from outside of the capabilities of the sensor. We will also ensure that any aggregated measures of the half hourly data (e.g.daily average) dont have too little measurements to create bias. For quality control, we will covert suspect or unreliable measurements to a NA.

Using packages

First, you need to reorganize the date and time in the timestamp to better work with the data. In the last activity, you learned how to work with date formatting. There is a package called lubridate that has helpful functions for working with dates and times in R. Packages contain a suite of related functions that are not available in base R. These functions are useful to enough people to make them available, but they arent considered a fundamental enough function to include in the base R. There are currently over 10,000 packages on CRAN (network that makes R available). It would take up a lot of space to download all of these packages and many of these packages may use the same name for functions that perform differently. This is why all of the functions in these packages are not readily available for base R. However, some functions in these additional packages can be useful and you will want to use them in your script when necessary. The first step is making sure you install the package on your local computer. You only need this command if you have never installed the package on the computer or you recently updated your version of R.

#use install.packages to install lubridate
install.packages(c("lubridate"))
#it is helpful to comment this line after you run this line of code on the computer
#and the package installs. You really don't want to do this over and over again.

Each time you want to use a package for your code, you will need to load the package to your current working environment. You only want to load a package when you are going to use it. This will help minimize any conflicts between function names. You use the library function to load a package to your R working environment. You use this function with every script that uses the packages, each time you run the code for the script.

library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date, intersect, setdiff, union

Youll notice a warning package that the function date in base R will be over-ridden by the date function in lubridate. This is a good example of why you want to only work with necessary packages because they can easily lead to confusion.

Working with dates

Lubridate is helpful for handling date and time data and creating standardized formats. Lets use lubridate to standardize both the date and time. You can always find a description of all of the functions in R by searching for the package and finding the pdf of the package description from CRAN. Below is an example of the description for a function that parses dates and times. You use the name of the function to indicate the format of your time.

The date is formated m/d/Y H:M, and for this function you just need to indicate the order but not the formatting.

#convert to standardized format
#date format is m/d/y
dates <- mdy_hm(datW$timestamp, tz= "America/New_York")

Now that the date is standardized, we can use some helpful functions from lubridate that I like to use. The doy function calculates the continuous day of year. For example, January 1st is doy = 1 and December 31 is doy = 365 during a non-leap year. I find this very helpful for plotting and occasionally for calculations involving time. Other helpful measures include an isolated hour measurement and decimal day of year which includes the hours within day of year.

#calculate day of year
datW$doy <- yday(dates)
#calculate hour in the day
datW$hour <- hour(dates) + (minute(dates)/60)
#calculate decimal day of year
datW$DD <- datW$doy + (datW$hour/24)
#quick preview of new date calcualtions
datW[1,]
##         timestamp solar.radiation precipitation lightning.acvitivy

Youll see in the preview above that an observation on June 12 at 11:30 is on doy 163, at hour 11.5, and is actually at 163.479 when we consider the hours into the doy.

Checking missing data

As you read in the manual, there are many quality control measurements that are built into the sensor datalogger. The data logger may indicate that the data from a sensor is an NA if it considers it to be in an unreliable range. Lets start by taking a look at how much data we are missing. If there is too much data missing, the researcher needs to go check that their equipment is installed properly and still functioning.

You can run a line of code to help do an initial check for missing data. Ive mentioned in class that R doesnt deal with NAs like a character or a number. NA is in its own special class. Youll need to use the functions in R specifically designed for NAs. The is.na function is meant to return a TRUE/FALSE answer where TRUE indicates a NA is present. The which function indicates all elements in the vector where the items in the function return a TRUE value. If you remember from last class length returns the length of the vector. When all three statements are used together, the result will be the number of NAs present in each column of data. Lets look at the variables the researchers are interested in.

#see how many values have missing data for each sensor observation
#air temperature
length(which(is.na(datW$air.temperature)))

Setting up tests for QA/QC

Visual checks

There are many ways to do QA/QC. For small datasets, an initial check on a plot can often capture a lot of elements for QA/QC. However, for large datasets, a visual check of the data is impossible and insufficient. More quantitative measures can also help reinforce the expectations and assumptions associated with the data.

Lets start with air temperature. Looking at a plot will help familiarize you with the data.

#make a plot with filled in points (using pch)
#line lines
plot(datW$DD, datW$air.temperature, pch=19, type="b", xlab = "Day of Year",
     ylab="Air temperature (degrees C)")

We can see that the data looks reasonable. We dont have any extreme spikes in observations and the fluctuations look like typical daily variation. Watch for odd repeating patterns, extreme jumps in values in a short period of time (1-2 hours), or unrealistic values. If there are extreme jumps in values, it would be helpful to look at metrics like the change in temperature with each half hour. We dont have to worry about that here because the datalogger does a good job of quality assurance. Before we go any further, lets establish how to convert unreliable data to NA. Well use an example that isnt a problem in our data just to illustrate the code. In this summer dataset, I know that I should not observe any air temperature values below freezing. I will specify that any values below freezing should be considered as missing data for an example.

#I'm going to make a new column to work with that indicates that I am conducting QAQC
#because overwriting values should be done cautiously and can lead to confusing issues.
#It can be particularly confusing when you are just learning R.
#Here I'm using the ifelse function
#the first argument is a logical statement to be evaluated as true or false on a vector
#the second argument is the value that my air.tempQ1 column will be given if the statement
#is true. The last value is the value that will be given to air.tempQ1 if the statement is false.
#In this case it is just given the air temperature value
datW$air.tempQ1 <- ifelse(datW$air.temperature < 0, NA, datW$air.temperature)

Realistic values

The next step is to check the range of the more extreme values. We want to make sure the data range that is collected is realistic. There are a couple of measurements that look very high and very low. Lets investigate. The quantile function returns the values of data for a given frequency of data. The 50% quantile is the value in the data where 50% of the values are above it and 50% of the values are below it. This is the median. The 0% quantile means that no data occurs below that value and that value is the minimum . The 100% quantile means that all data occurs below the value and that value is the maximum.

#check the values at the extreme range of the data
#and throughout the percentiles
quantile(datW$air.tempQ1)
##   0%  25%  50%  75% 100% 
##  7.0 16.2 20.1 23.3 34.4

Some statisticians and data scientists like to filter extreme values using quantiles. For example, some outlier tests remove values that occur less than 5% or 1% of the time. These tests should be used with caution and limited to data that appears to be suspect with extreme spikes. In weather data, record highs or lows can often be reliably measured by instruments. We dont want to filter them out just because these values dont occur very often. In fact, these extreme values are often of interest for many different applications.

The maximum and minimum values in this dataset seem infrequent for this area, but not impossible. Since air temperature is corrected with solar radiation and wind data, extreme values in calculations can often occur due to numerical artifacts of the way the calculations can be structured. It would be good to check that these extreme values really are accurate. Unfortunately, there are no half hourly weather stations to compare the data to nearby that can be readily downloaded for analysis. However, you can find a visualization of historic weather data by day. Lets do the comparison. First, lets take a look at the days that have these extreme observations.

Measurements outside of sensor capabilities

If you continue reading in the manual, you will find the section pictured below that explains that measurements (mainly wind and air temperature) may be unreliable when there is heavy wind and strong rain.

In this area, these kinds of events in the summer typically occur as thunderstorms. Since the wind sensor may be unreliable during this time, lets use precipitation and the lightning sensor to mark any air temperature and wind data that would be unreliable. First lets take a look at both values on the same plot.

#plot precipitation and lightning strikes on the same plot
#normalize lighting strikes to match precipitation
lightscale <- (max(datW$precipitation)/max(datW$lightning.acvitivy)) * datW$lightning.acvitivy
#make the plot with precipitation and lightning activity marked
#make it empty to start and add in features
plot(datW$DD , datW$precipitation, xlab = "Day of Year", ylab = "Precipitation & lightning",
        type="n")
#plot precipitation points only when there is precipitation 
#make the points semi-transparent
points(datW$DD[datW$precipitation > 0], datW$precipitation[datW$precipitation > 0],
        col= rgb(95/255,158/255,160/255,.5), pch=15)        
        
#plot lightning points only when there is lightning     
points(datW$DD[lightscale > 0], lightscale[lightscale > 0],
        col= "tomato3", pch=19)

You can see from the plot there are points when there is lightning and high rain. Lets filter all values with lightning that coincides with rainfall greater than 2mm or only rainfall over 5 mm.

#filter out storms in wind and air temperature measurements
# filter all values with lightning that coincides with rainfall greater than 2mm or only rainfall over 5 mm.    
#create a new air temp column
datW$air.tempQ2 <- ifelse(datW$precipitation  >= 2 & datW$lightning.acvitivy >0, NA,
                    ifelse(datW$precipitation > 5, NA, datW$air.tempQ1))

Finishing your QA/QC

You talked to the researchers about the missing soil temperature and moisture data. They looked at their field notes and have more information. They noted that in mid-July the weather station had been tampered with. The soil moisture and temperature sensor was found lying on top of the ground and the cable pulled out of the datalogger. If the soil moisture and temperature sensor loses contact with the ground, the measurements will be unreliable. Sudden changes in the sensor position in the ground are marked by dramatic changes in soil temperature and moisture. Although its likely something pulled out the sensor from the ground simultaneously unplugging the cable, you will want to check that this is a reasonable expectation.
